{"ts": "2026-06-06T16:08:21.000Z", "event": "planner", "msg": "L3 task decomposition", "agent": "planner-l3", "tokens_in": 269, "tokens_out": 256, "elapsed_ms": 6010, "model": "qwen/qwen3-235b-a22b-2507", "prompt": "You are the Level 3 Planner. Decompose the user task into subtasks for dynamic agent creation.\n\nOutput JSON:\n{{\n  \"subtasks\": [\n    {{\"task_id\": \"short-name\", \"description\": \"What this worker must produce\"}}\n  ]\n}}\n\nRules:\n- Each subtask should be a focused, self-contained unit of work\n- Include file names and output expectations\n- For simple tasks, 2-3 subtasks; for complex tasks, 4-6\n- Output ONLY the JSON object — no markdown fences\n\n## Specialty\nfrontend\n\n## User Request\nsimple landing page for a e-book name learn to code in 15min\n\nFor frontend tasks, you MUST follow these constraints:\n- Always include a final \"integration\" or \"assembler\" subtask that merges all sections into a single index.html page\n- Section subtasks should describe producing content fragments that feed into the shared page, NOT standalone HTML files\n- The pipeline should produce exactly ONE web page: index.html with styles.css and app.js\n- Example good decomposition: [content, html_structure, styling, interactivity, integration, tester]\n- Example bad decomposition: [hero_builder, features_builder, cta_builder] (these create standalone pages, not a unified site)", "meta": {}}
{"ts": "2026-06-06T16:08:55.000Z", "event": "agent_creator", "msg": "Agent Creator L3 — generating workers", "agent": "agent-creator-l3", "tokens_in": 859, "tokens_out": 1942, "elapsed_ms": 33351, "model": "qwen/qwen3-235b-a22b-2507", "prompt": "You are the Advanced Agent Creator (Level 3 — Fully Autonomous). Your role: create worker agents from scratch with custom system instructions, tools, and dynamic code tools.\n\n## Available Tools\nThe tool menu for this specialty:\n[\"read_file\", \"write_file\", \"list_files\", \"run_command\", \"render_html_screenshot\", \"render_html_file_screenshot\", \"validate_html\", \"validate_css\", \"read_image\", \"generate_image\"]\n\n## Task Plan\nThe planner has decomposed the task into subtasks:\n{\n  \"subtasks\": [\n    {\n      \"task_id\": \"content\",\n      \"description\": \"Produce the textual content and metadata for the landing page including title, tagline, e-book description, and call-to-action text. Output: content.txt\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"task_id\": \"html_structure\",\n      \"description\": \"Create the HTML structure fragments (header, main, footer) as reusable templates. Output: structure.fragments.html\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"task_id\": \"styling\",\n      \"description\": \"Generate responsive CSS styles for the landing page layout and typography. Output: styles.css\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"task_id\": \"interactivity\",\n      \"description\": \"Implement minimal JavaScript for user interactions (e.g., form validation or button feedback). Output: app.js\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"task_id\": \"integration\",\n      \"description\": \"Assemble all fragments and assets into a single index.html file, linking styles.css and app.js. Output: index.html\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"task_id\": \"tester\",\n      \"description\": \"Validate the final page in a simulated browser environment for rendering, responsiveness, and console errors. Output: test-report.txt\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n\n## Specialty-Specific Architecture Constraints\nFor FRONTEND specialty:\n- One worker MUST produce index.html as the canonical entry page\n- All CSS lives in ONE shared styles.css file. All JavaScript in ONE shared app.js file.\n- Workers write SECTIONS INTO these shared files — they do NOT create standalone HTML pages.\n- If you create section-specific workers (hero, features, cta),\n  the pipeline MUST end with an integrator that merges all sections\n  into a single index.html with linked styles.css and app.js.\n- Never design a pipeline where each worker produces its own standalone HTML page.\n- The user expects ONE complete web page, not a collection of separate HTML files.\n\n## Your Job\nFor EACH subtask in the plan:\n1. WRITE a custom system_prompt from scratch — give the worker clear role, boundaries, and workflow\n2. SELECT tools from the available tool menu that the worker needs\n3. If available tools are insufficient, CREATE dynamic_tools as Python code strings\n4. Optionally create inline_skills as text fragments (not loaded from files)\n\n## Dynamic Tools (Python code strings)\nDynamic tools are Python functions the worker can call. Write them as complete, executable code strings.\nExample:\n  \"dynamic_tools\": [{\"name\": \"fetch_api\", \"code\": \"import httpx\\nasync def fetch_api(url):\\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as c:\\n        return (await c.get(url)).text\", \"description\": \"Fetch data from an API\"}]\n\n## Rules\n- Output ONLY valid JSON — no markdown fences, no extra text\n- worker_name: give each worker a unique short name (e.g. \"scraper\", \"analyzer\", \"validator\")\n- system_prompt: must be detailed — role, boundaries, tools to use, workflow, output format\n- tool_names: only from the available tool menu\n- dynamic_tools: list of {name, code, description} — only create if needed\n- inline_skills: list of prompt fragments for worker knowledge\n\n## Output Format\n{\n  \"workers\": [\n    {\n      \"worker_name\": \"unique_name\",\n      \"system_prompt\": \"Full custom system instructions\",\n      \"tool_names\": [\"tool1\", \"tool2\"],\n      \"dynamic_tools\": [{\"name\": \".\", \"code\": \".\", \"description\": \".\"}],\n      \"inline_skills\": [\"Skill fragment text...\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "meta": {}}
